==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=masquerade}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} ''[[mascarade]]'' ({{etyl|es|en}} ''[[mascarada]]''), from {{etyl|it|en}} ''[[mascarata]]'' (''[[mascherata]]''). See “[[mask]]”.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|eɪd|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[party]] or [[assembly]] of people wearing [[mask]]s, and [[amusing]] themselves with [[dancing]], [[conversation]], or other [[diversions]].
#: In courtly balls and midnight '''masquerades''' - [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]
# {{lb|en|fandom}} A [[cosplay]] [[event]] at which costumed attendees perform [[skit]]s on a [[stage]].
# {{label|en|obsolete}} A [[dramatic]] [[performance]] by [[actor]]s in masks; a mask. See “[[mask]]”
# [[acting|Acting]] or [[living]] under [[false]] [[pretense]]s; [[concealment]] of something by a false or unreal show; [[pretentious]] show; [[disguise]].
#: ''I was invited to the '''masquerade''' at their home.''
#: That '''masquerade''' of misrepresentation which invariably accompanied the political eloquence of Rome - [[w:Thomas de Quincey|Thomas de Quincey]]
# {{label|en|archaic}} A [[Spanish]] [[entertainment]] in which [[squadron]]s of [[horse]]s charge at each other, the riders fighting with [[buckler]]s and [[cane]]s.

